{
  "items": [
    {
      "prompt": "Your tomato plants show yellowing lower leaves despite adequate watering and light. Review the standard NPK selection steps: identify symptoms, determine nutrient deficiency type (N-P-K), then choose an amendment. What specific symptom combination confirms a Nitrogen deficit versus Phosphorus or Potassium issues? Explain why applying high-nitrogen fertilizer based on leaf color alone without confirming soil conditions might harm root health.",
      "answer": "Nitrogen typically causes uniform yellowing of lower leaves (chlorosis). Deficiency in P often shows purpling, while K causes scorch/browning at leaf tips/edges. Applying only nitrogen ignores underlying pH or compaction issues; if roots cannot access water/nutrients due to poor soil structure, extra N will be wasted and may cause salt buildup stressing the plant.",
      "rubric": "- Correctly identifies yellow lower leaves as primary Nitrogen symptom.\n- Distinguishes this from Phosphorus (purple) or Potassium (edge burn).\n- Explains that unaddressed soil issues render nitrogen ineffective or harmful.",
      "skill": "apply"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "You need to adjust pH in a container mix using bone meal and kelp extract. According to the amendment guide, these materials primarily address Phosphorus availability rather than Nitrogen uptake efficiency directly. If your test kit shows low available P but normal N levels, why is correcting pH critical for this specific choice over just adding more ammonium nitrate?",
      "answer": "Adding bone meal and kelp helps because phosphorus fixation increases as soil becomes too alkaline; acidic conditions free up nitrogen but can lock in phosphorus. Correcting the pH unlocks available P so roots can access it, whereas extra N does not solve the blockage caused by chemical interactions with lime-rich materials or compacted clay.",
      "rubric": "- Recognizes bone meal/kelp target Phosphorus availability over Nitrogen uptake.\n- Explains that low soil pH locks in phosphorus while high pH fixes nitrogen unnecessarily.\n- Connects pH correction to unlocking nutrients rather than just adding bulk fertilizer.",
      "skill": "apply"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "A student gardener claims: \"If my tomatoes look green and healthy, I can skip soil tests entirely.\" Evaluate this statement against the NPK selection logic. What real-world scenario involving heavy clay versus sandy loam demonstrates why visual cues alone cannot guide amendment choices for a full summer?",
      "answer": "Visual health hides internal nutrient imbalances; some plants tolerate excess nitrogen or low phosphorus until sudden failure occurs in container gardens with small root volumes compared to open ground. A soil test quantifies actual availability so amendments target deficiencies directly rather than guessing based on imperfect visual cues.",
      "rubric": "- Disagrees that visuals alone can guide NPK decisions due to hidden imbalances.\n- Notes the difference between tolerant species and those failing under stress or compaction.\n- Emphasizes soil texture differences (clay/sand) affecting nutrient availability regardless of plant appearance.",
      "skill": "critique"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

